# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2008-hong-kong-legislative-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1888-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] The **1888 Hong Kong Sanitary Board election** was held on 11 June 1888 for the two unofficial seats in the Sanitary Board of Hong Kong.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1888-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] Sanitary Board was set up in 1883 to supervise and control the practical sanitation of the colony.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1888-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] As its work involved interference with the private affairs of residents it was unpopular with property owners and with the Chinese generally.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1888-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] Their implementation was a matter for the Government.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1888-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] Originally it consisted solely of official members but subsequently provision was made for nominated unofficial members, and two members elected by ratepayers on the special and common jury lists.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1888-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] Of the 669 persons on the jury lists for the year, 213 voted, with 187 valid ballots and 23 spoiled ballots.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1888-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] It was the first ever election held in the history of Hong Kong.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1888-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] The elections continued as the Sanitary Board transformed into the Urban Council in 1936 and marked the beginning of the Hong Kong constitutional reform in the post-war period.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1888-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] The *Daily Press* hailed the occasion saying the day would be ranked as a day of note by the future historians of Hong Kong; for the first time the ratepayers of the Colony had been given a voice in the management of their own affairs.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1888-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] Francis was a leading member of the Hong Kong Association founded in 1893 for improving and popularising the Government.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1891-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] The **1891 Hong Kong Sanitary Board election** held on 17 June 1891 was the second election for the two unofficial seats in the Sanitary Board of Hong Kong.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1891-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] Only ratepayers on the jury lists of the year were eligible to vote.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1891-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] There were 256 out of the 445 persons of the electorate voted.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1891-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] Each elector could cast up to two votes.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1894-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] The **1894 Hong Kong Sanitary Board election** was an election held for the two unofficial seats in the Sanitary Board on 16 June 1894 but, there being only two candidates, the seats were filled uncontested.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1894-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] During the election, the 1894 Hong Kong plague devastated the colony and drew attention to the composition and power of the board.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1894-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] One proposal, supported by unofficial member of the Legislative Council Ho Kai, called for it to be upgraded to a municipal council with enhanced powers.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] A plebiscite on whether the Sanitary Board should have an official or unofficial majority was held in Hong Kong in June 1896.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] The result of the plebiscite was overwhelmingly for unofficial majority, however no constitutional changes were made for Sanitary Board, though the constitutions of the Executive and Legislative Council were changed as unofficial members were added as a result.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] The 1896 plebiscite is on record the only referendum conducted by the Hong Kong Government and could be seen as part of the first major debate on the constitutional reform in the crown colony during the 1890s.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] It was much earlier than the Governor Mark Aitchison Young's Young Plan in the 1940s and 1950s and the rise of the modern pro-democracy camp in the 1980s.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] The Sanitary Board was established in 1883 in responsible of improving the sanitary conditions in the city as the result of Osbert Chadwick's report in 1881 advised.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Three elections were held in 1888, 1891 and 1894 respectively.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] The bubonic plague of 1894 raised the question of the composition and powers of the Board.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] The Government's decision of appointing a Medical Officer of Health to the Board in 1895 was against the will of the unofficial members.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Francis, the three times elected member resigned, and other three unofficial members Ho Kai, William Hartigan and Robert Kennaway Leigh followed.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] The members of the Executive Council and the Chamber of Commerce were dissatisfied the sanitation and ineffectiveness of the Board.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Keswick of the Chamber of Commerce, Paul Chater and E.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Belilios were in favour of an official majority while the officers directly responsible to the Governor.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Contrast to the abolition of the Board, Ho Kai represented another opinion of maintaining the unofficial majority and larger power of the unofficial members.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Governor William Robinson shared the same view with the former, insisted that a Medical Department with a Principal Civil Medical Officer directly under the Government should replace the Sanitary Board.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] With regard of the reconstitution of the Sanitary Board, Governor William Robinson conducted a plebiscite in June 1896.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Besides the reconstitution of the Sanitary Board issues, in 1894 there was a group of petitioners supported by the Unofficial Members of the Legislative Council Paul Chater and Ho Kai with 363 signatures asked for a further representations in the Colonial Government.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Perfect freedom of debate for the Official Members with power to vote according to their conscientious convictions.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Complete control in the Council over local expenditure.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] A consultative voice in questions of an Imperial character.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Although the Governor and the Acting Colonial Secretary Stewart Lockhart, J.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Belilios opposed the reform, Lord Ripon agreed with increasing the number of unofficial members in the Legislative Council, introducing unofficial element into the Executive Council and creating a Municipal Council.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] The electorates were limited to persons only on the jury lists of the year.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] There were 788 persons in total out of the 250,000 population in Hong Kong and 362 votes were cast.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Most of entitled voters were from the British community.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Among them there were three or four Chinese voted for the unofficials and none voted for the officials.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Although the majority of the Chinese population was unrepresented, the result was overwhelmingly favour for the unofficial majority.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Although the plebiscite showed a clear view for unofficial majority, Robinson still insisted to have sanitary affairs placed directly under Government control.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Chamberlain refused any constitutional changes to the Sanitary Board.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] The election for the unofficial members resumed in 1899.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] The Sanitary Department was not established until the Public Health and Buildings Ordinance was passed in 1903.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Hong Kong had to wait until 1936 and the creation of the Urban Council for any further advance toward a municipal council.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Nevertheless, the other two suggestions by Lord Ripon were soon carried out, an unofficial member and an official member appointed to the Legislative Council respectively and two unofficial members who were the senior members the Legislative Council appointed to the Executive Council.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Wei Yuk was the newly appointed unofficial member to the Legislative Council as one of the two Chinese representative alongside Ho Kai who had been the member since 1890.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1896-hong-kong-sanitary-board-plebiscite] Paul Chater and Jardine representative John Bell-Irving were the new unofficial members appointed to the Executive Council.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1899-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] The **1899 Hong Kong Sanitary Board election** was supposed to be held on 18 December 1899 for the two unofficial seats in the Sanitary Board of British Hong Kong.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1899-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] Only persons on the jury lists of the year were eligible to vote.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1899-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] There were only two candidates therefore only 19 votes were cast as a formality.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1899-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] Prior to the election, the issue of reconstitution of the Sanitary Board was intensively debated.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1899-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] A plebiscite of the British community based on the jury lists was held in June 1896, as to whether Sanitary Board should contain an official or unofficial majority.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1899-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] The Government refused to make any further constitutional changes however the election for unofficial members was not held until 1899.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1899-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] Dr William Hartigan and James McKie were elected.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1899-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] They both resigned in April 1901 to protest that the Board was given too few powers.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1901-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] The **1901 Hong Kong Sanitary Board election** was supposed to be held on 15 April 1901 for the vacancies of two unofficial seats on the Sanitary Board of Hong Kong.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1901-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] Only ratepayers who were included in the special and common jury lists of that year, or ratepayers who were exempted from serving on juries on account of their professional vocations were entitled to vote in the election.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1901-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] That month, the two elected members on the Sanitary Board had resigned in protest of limitations placed on their powers.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1901-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] No nominations were received for the April election, the public being highly dissatisfied with the Board's conduct.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1903-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] The **1903 Hong Kong Sanitary Board election** was held on 25 March 1903 was the second election for the two unofficial seats in the Sanitary Board of Hong Kong under the reconstituted Public Health and Building Ordinance of 1903.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1903-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] Only ratepayers who were included in the Special and Common Jury Lists of the years or ratepayers who are exempted from serving on Juries on account of their professional avocations were entitled to vote at the election.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/1903-hong-kong-sanitary-board-election] Henry Edward Pollock, the former Acting Attorney General and the member of the Executive and Legislative Council was elected.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The **2008 Hong Kong Legislative Council election** was held on 7 September 2008 for the 4th Legislative Council since the establishment of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] There were 60 seats in the 4th Legislative Council, with 30 members elected by geographical constituencies through direct elections, and 30 members by functional constituencies.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] Candidates for 14 functional constituency seats were unopposed.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The turnout rate was 45 percent with 1.51 million voters casting the ballots, about 10 percent lower than the previous election in 2004.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The duo resigned from their party positions and Chow resigned from the Executive Council after the election, which was followed by a great split of the party.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] In the backdrop of a deteriorating economy and rising inflation, the pro-grassroots parties scored victories as the new pro-democracy party League of Social Democrats (LSD) had their three candidates elected and the FTU also won in two seats in the geographical constituencies.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The share of the pan-democratic parties' vote among voters dropped from 60 percent in 2004 to 57 percent, which translated into a net loss of two seats compared to the last election.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The pan-democrats were elected to a total of 23 seats, 19 seats in the directly elected geographical constituencies, and four seats from the functional constituencies.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] By virtue of having in excess of one-third of the seats in Legislative Council, their ability to veto constitutional changes remained intact.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The pan-democrats' veto power was seen as crucial for the electoral arrangements for the 2012 Legislative Council election, which would take place during this session.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The Standing Committee of the National People's Congress vote in December 2007 to allow universal suffrage by 2017, and full Legislative Council elections by 2020, tempered the debate on universal suffrage.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] Wary of political parties, the government sought to defer discussion on other highly sensitive issues until October 2008, in the hopes that the election will be void of focus.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The election was therefore fought over issues regarding the minimum wage, health care reform, Old Age Allowance, and the future of RTHK.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] Also, the case surrounding former Housing Director Leung Chin-man served to highlight the issue of systematic checks and balances, and the lack of political scrutiny of government actions.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] Commentators, such as Albert Cheng, noted that the fighting between pro-democracy parties was heating up, but forecast few changes in the overall party standings of the new Council.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] He cited proportional representation as a mechanism, which built in protection for a multi-party system.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] There were some concerns that those seeking the right of abode in Hong Kong felt pressured by lobbyists supporting the DAB.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] Two advocacy groups echoed abode-seekers' in being bombarded with telephone calls and other pressures to vote for the DAB, or for Regina Ip.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] A total of 142 candidates on 53 lists entered the election via the geographical constituencies, making it the most contested election since the handover of Hong Kong.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The candidates of both the pan-democracy and pro-Beijing coalitions stated that they would not allocate the votes within each camp, leading to infighting inside the caucuses.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] Martin Lee and Anson Chan announced that they would not stand, and would endorse other candidates.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] In addition, some incumbent legislators such as Audrey Eu of the Civic Party and Yeung Sum of the Democratic Party were placed second on their lists in an attempt to get less experienced members of their parties elected.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] Beijing's involvement in the elections was an open secret: its strategy was to elect a new batch of "independent" aspirants with profession backgrounds and without a strong pro-Beijing image, such as Scarlet Pong, and eventual winners Regina Ip and Priscilla Leung.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] It had hoped they would appeal to the middle class voters and steal votes from the pan-democratic parties.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The functional constituencies were less competitive: 14 out of the 30 seats were uncontested.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The Accounting and Architectural, Surveying and Planning functional constituencies were the most contested, with 5 candidates competing in each constituency.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] 45 candidates in total ran for the 16 contested seats.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] Ten incumbents chose not to run for re-election.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] A record number of 3.37 million people registered to vote in the election.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The turnout rate was low, at 45% with 1.51 million voters casting ballots.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] Commentator Chris Yeung believed that the Liaison Office operated behind the scenes to co-ordinate votes for the pro-Beijing camp.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] These independents managed to secure seats, but apparently not at the expense of support for the pan-democrats.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The Democratic Alliance for the Betterment of Hong Kong remained the largest single party in Council, with 13 seats.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The share of the pan-democratic parties' vote among voters dropped from 60% in 2004 to 57%, which translated into a net loss of 2 seats.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] By virtue of having in excess of 1⁄3 of the seats in LegCo, their ability to veto constitutional changes remained intact.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The pan-democrats' veto power were crucial for the electoral arrangements for the 2012 elections, which will take place during this Council.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] In the backdrop of a deteriorating economy and rising inflation, voters shifted their preferences towards more radical and grass-roots politicians; the electorate's suspicions of collusion between government and big business dealt a blow to the Liberal Party.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The Liberal Party suffered double defeat when Selina Chow and chairman James Tien lost their seats in the New Territories West and New Territories East geographical constituencies respectively.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] Their bid to secure seats in other constituencies also failed.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] Tien resigned as the Liberal Party's chairman after his defeat, and Chow resigned both her vice-chairmanship and her seat on the Executive Council of Hong Kong.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The election of three members of the League of Social Democrats and four trade-unionists to Legco is set to pose a challenge to the government on welfare and livelihood issues.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] Note: Candidates in 14 functional constituencies were elected uncontested to the Legislative Council.
[src:2008-hong-kong-legislative-election/2008-hong-kong-legislative-election] The number of seats for the Hong Kong Federation of Trade Unions in the geographical constituencies exclude Wong Kwok-hing, Wong Kwok-kin and Pan Pey Chyou, who are also DAB members; figures in parentheses in the pan-democracy and pro-Beijing total percentage exclude all votes of other individuals.
